    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4049198443" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4049198443" />
    <a title="Monty Milne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14797192-monty-milne"><img alt="Monty Milne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1363450934p2/14797192.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4049198443?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monty Milne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monty Milne" href="/user/show/14797192-monty-milne">Monty Milne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4049198443" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15165509620404142121">This is a strange and remarkable book. At first I loved it, then became a bit bogged down and wondered if it was all a bit overdone, and then ended up loving it again. By the time I got to the end, I had the conviction it was definitely a masterpiece and it has left me with deep and lasting impressions.<br/><br/>The prose is dense and opaque and at times almost impossibly purple. Sentences go on and on and it is fatiguing to try and extract the sense of what can feel like tedious gibberish – if you are no</span>
  <span id="freeText15165509620404142121" style="display:none">This is a strange and remarkable book. At first I loved it, then became a bit bogged down and wondered if it was all a bit overdone, and then ended up loving it again. By the time I got to the end, I had the conviction it was definitely a masterpiece and it has left me with deep and lasting impressions.<br /><br />The prose is dense and opaque and at times almost impossibly purple. Sentences go on and on and it is fatiguing to try and extract the sense of what can feel like tedious gibberish – if you are not in the right mood for it. I have been experimenting lately with intermittent fasting and I found this worked best for me when I approached the text in the kind of heightened awareness that a period of fasting brings – a kind of relaxed attentiveness, if that doesn’t sound too contradictory. When I was in the right frame of mind, the poetry of the text had an almost hallucinatory effect, giving sensations of velvet and brocade, polychromatic, shimmering with light. (Perhaps I’ve been overdoing the fasting…)<br /><br />My German is too basic to read this except in English translation, but I presume for those who can and do read it in German, this provides a much better experience. The Translator, in an excellent preface, points out that English aims for brevity and lucidity, and achieves richness “by the exfoliation of the subject in a successive and natural development, rather than by trying to sound multiple levels of meaning at once.” German, by contrast, explores richness with long, complex, multi-dimensional sentences. With some texts, English is better if you want to tease out the meaning (which is why a German once told me that it was easier for him to read German philosophy in English translation!) But for those whose skills allow for it, the poetic multi-layered richness of Broch’s original text must surely be better than any translation.<br /><br />This is far more than a meditation on the last eighteen hours of Virgil’s life. Of course Virgil’s Aeneid is a key part of our shared inheritance, even if we haven’t read it in its entirety (although to read Dryden’s version right through for the first time, as I did a few years ago, is to recognise what you’ve already known from a thousand other sources). But this is also a meditation – a kind of epiphany even – on the experience of death. And it is by no means depressing, but indescribably beautiful, haunting and life affirming. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15165509620404142121" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


