    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_194813961" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/194813961" />
    <a title="Asa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1904061-asa"><img alt="Asa" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/194813961?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asa" href="/user/show/1904061-asa">Asa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9789174864748" href="/book/show/25713722-vergilii-d-d">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1904061-asa?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer194813961" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer687225067396974676">The death of Virgil is a book that really didn&apos;t work for me, and I&apos;ve spent some time trying to figure out why. It wasn&apos;t because of the obvious things - bad writing, one-dimensional characters, uninteresting plot - or because of a pet peeve, but I had to force myself to finish it. <br/><br/>For me, books are made out of four building blocks: Characters, Plot, Setting and Language. It varies from book to book how they are used and how important they are, and all readers have different opinions about whic</span>
  <span id="freeText687225067396974676" style="display:none">The death of Virgil is a book that really didn't work for me, and I've spent some time trying to figure out why. It wasn't because of the obvious things - bad writing, one-dimensional characters, uninteresting plot - or because of a pet peeve, but I had to force myself to finish it. <br /><br />For me, books are made out of four building blocks: Characters, Plot, Setting and Language. It varies from book to book how they are used and how important they are, and all readers have different opinions about which one(s) matter to them. Plot is most obvious in mysteries, thrillers or adventure stories, where you read to find out what happens. When it comes to character I think of authors like Jane Austen or Shakespeare, where there has been a lot of adaptations into different times or environments, like Clueless or Bridget Jones' diary for Austen and Baz Luhrmann's Romeo + Juliet or Ran, Kurosawa's version of King Lear, for Shakespeare. Setting is the opposite, where if you try to move the plot and characters somewhere else a lot of the book is lost, like Kipling's Kim or Wharton's The age of innocence. My favorite writers when it comes to language is Virginia Woolf and and Patrick O'Brian, where it almost doesn't matter what they write because I will read it and like it.<br /><br />What I've discovered is that while I talk and think about the characters the most, love an interesting and vivid setting, and can take or leave plot, the real deal breaker for me is the language. If I love how the author writes I can read and enjoy almost any book even if the content isn't something I would normally pick, if I'm neutral or don't notice the writing I can like the other parts, but if the language doesn't work for me I can't enjoy the book at all. I don't mean obvious bad writing - spelling mistakes, clumsy sentences or a lack in editing - but language that for some reason rubs me the wrong way and makes it impossible for me to focus on the rest of the book.<br /><br />In this book, Virgil is dying (see the title) and on his deathbed, while feverish and hallucinating, he looks back on his life and work and feels that he has failed in what he tried to do, which was to create a work of art that would both mirror the real world and show how to make it better. While talking to his friends and the emperor Virgil tries to explain why he feels this way, and how false art shouldn't be preserved or read and that therefore he wants to burn the Aeneid, and in between he has these really intense images or hallucinations. These images go on for pages and pages, without any breaks or pauses, with the sentences that never seemed to end and repeated the same things over and over with some variations, and as the book went on and Virgil slipped away he became more and more metaphysical in the way he described the universe. This is where the author lost me, because while I was reading I stopped focusing and often I came to the end of a page and had no memory of what I'd just read, because the way he described things just slid away. It isn't just the subject or the experimenal writing, since my favorite Woolf is The waves, so I've come to realize that it's Broch's language that throws me out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="687225067396974676" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

