  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1943445955" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1943445955" />
    <a title="Elena" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5871422-elena"><img alt="Elena" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1489767140p2/5871422.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1943445955?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena" href="/user/show/5871422-elena">Elena</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9783518388662" href="/book/show/2769067-der-tod-des-vergil">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1943445955" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3893655606975735355">The beginning of &quot;Der Tod des Vergil&quot; is graced with a few quotations including the famous &quot;fato profugus,&quot; and while Broch began the book in Europe, he finished it in exile in the US, part of a distinguished circle of emigre writers who helped and supported, and fought with, each other. Thomas Mann and Albert Einstein were close friends. Exile is the subtext.<br/><br/>I was inspired to read this novel after reading Yourcenar&apos;s &quot;Memoirs of Hadrian.&quot; It interested me how European intellectuals struggled wi</span>
  <span id="freeText3893655606975735355" style="display:none">The beginning of "Der Tod des Vergil" is graced with a few quotations including the famous "fato profugus," and while Broch began the book in Europe, he finished it in exile in the US, part of a distinguished circle of emigre writers who helped and supported, and fought with, each other. Thomas Mann and Albert Einstein were close friends. Exile is the subtext.<br /><br />I was inspired to read this novel after reading Yourcenar's "Memoirs of Hadrian." It interested me how European intellectuals struggled with their cultural legacy during the rise of fascism, and poured much of their thoughts and feelings into works like these. "Der Tod des Vergil" book takes place 19 BC in a sort of "real time" stream of consciousness. So while Virgil is suffering from fever and hallucinations during the last night of his life in Brindisi, the text takes as many hour to read as it took Virgil to get through to dawn. Or longer, I read the book on and off for four months. Brace yourself. The language is Wagnerian: it worked best for me to think of the text as an opera score, and just enjoy the onward rush of language, endless invented descriptive compound nouns (one of the creative aspects of the German language (try "Himmelsverborgenheiten."), along with endless pleonasm, seeming contradictions ("Vor-Echo kuenftigen Klanges") lots of leitmotif going on, and abrupt symphonic changes of tempo. The basic plot is pretty clear and close to history, so no worry about spoilers. We know Virgil is about to die, we know he has almost completed his masterpiece the Aeneid. And although we know he wants to destroy the manuscript, we all know it survived. The beauty is in the gorgeous, sometimes bombastic language, rather parallel to Wagner's gorgeous, bombastic music. The text incorporates quotations from various works by Virgil, some in custom German translations by a fellow refugee, these are enchanting, making it clear why his poetry was so loved over the centuries.<br /><br />Since I know absolutely nothing about the history of ancient Rome--a recent tour of the ruins only confused me more, I relied pretty heavily on Google searches to get the references. It seems that Virgil was one of the few pagan writers revered by the early Christians due to a few brief references to the coming of a savior, which they interpreted as prophesy of Christ. Broch includes lots of references to a mysterious, long awaited Heilbringer. I tried to find evidence of any ancient Virgil manuscripts, they all seem to have been copied and recopied in the Middle Ages, so I kept wondering if the manuscript was preserved because it contained prophetic references to Christ, or if the prophetic references were added at some point in order to justify preserving Virgil's divine poetry.<br /><br />Virgil has long discussions about beauty, and truth, and "Erkenntnis" with a couple literary friends. The heart of the book is an argument between the dying poet and the triumphantly victorious new emperor, Octavian Caesar Augustus. The poet doesn't think the Aeneid is good enough, the emperor demands that he relinquish it to be published (I assume professionally copied). Here there are some jarring anachronisms, like referring to the manuscript as paper, when paper had not yet reached Europe, but no mind, the argument is interesting. There are ironic bits, so Virgil says that Caesar's work will endure after his poem is forgotten, and we know the reverse is true...In the end the emperor needs the work as a foundation myth for his empire and he will get his way. The argument takes place during a swarm of small earthquakes that shake the ground, and a couple mysterious nonexistent figures drift in and out: a preternaturally insightful Greek peasant boy Lysanias, an odd "Eastern" slave who constantly contradicts the emperor (who doesn't hear), and Plotia, an old unconsummated flame of sorts. Virgil eventually relents and lets the emperor have the unfinished masterpiece. Virgil makes one dying request, that his slaves be freed, even though this will have a negative financial impact on his heirs. <br /><br />The emperor gets his book. He needs a magnificent foundation narrative that links him with greatness, so with Greece and with heroic ancestors. The book is saved because it is needed. As Virgil dies he seems to go through the biblical creation story in reverse, and seems to visit some sort of peaceable kingdom. After stretching language for 500 pages, Virgil lands somewhere beyond words.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3893655606975735355" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


